    </p>
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="Problem_OE3_6">
    <title>Problem 8_3_6a</title>
    <p>
        Supppose <m>r</m> is a primitive root modulo <m>p^k</m> and that <m>r</m> is odd. We show that <m>r</m> is a primitive root modulo <m>2p^k.</m> Clearly <m>\text{gcd}(r, 2p^k)=1.</m> Let <m>h=\text{ord}_{2p^k}(r).</m> Then,  <m>h | \phi(2p^k).</m> 
    </p>
    <p>
        Since <md>
            a^h \equiv 1 \pmod{2p^k},
        </md>

        also <md>
            a^h \equiv 1 \pmod{p^k}
        </md>
        and hence <md>
            \phi(p^k)|h
        </md>
        since <m>r</m> has order <m>\phi(p^k)</m> modulo <m>p^k.</m> But, <m>\phi(p^k)=\phi(2p^k)</m> and hence <m>h=\phi(2p^k).</m>
        
        
        
    </p>

    <p>
        For the converse if <m>r</m> is even is can't be a primitive root modulo <m>2p^k.</m>
    </p>
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="Problem_OE3_7">
    <title>Problem 9_1_5c</title>
    <p>
        Since <m>a</m> is a quadratic residue we know <md>
            a^{\frac{p-1}{2}}\equiv 1 \pmod{p}
        </md>
        
        We need only check:
        <md>
            (\pm a^{(p+1)/4})^2=a^{(p+1)/2}=a^{\frac{p-1}{2}+1} \equiv a \pmod{p}
        </md>

        which doesn't seem to have anything to do with <m>p \equiv 3 \pmod{4}</m>

        I think I am misinterpreting the negative sign.

        Let's write <md>
            \left((p-a)^{(p+1)/4}\right)^2= \left((p-a)^{(p+1)/2}\right)
        </md>
        
    </p>
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="Problem_OE3_8">
    <title>Problem 9_1_7</title>
<p>
    Let <m>p=2^k+1</m> be prime.
    If <m>\text{gcd}(a,p)=1</m>, we compute, assuming <m>a</m> is a quadratic non-residue:
    <md>
        a^{(p-1)/2}=a^{2^{k-1}} =a^{\phi(p)/2} \equiv -1.
    </md>

    If <m>a</m> is not a primitive root, then <m>a^{\phi(p)/2} \not \equiv -1</m>
  
</p>
</subsection>

