<subsection xml:id="Problem_OE3_12">
    <title>Problem 9_3_9</title>
<p>
    If <m>p=q+4a</m>, then <m>-q \equiv 4a \pmod{p}</m> which gives
    <md>
        \left(\frac{4a}{p}\right)=\left(\frac{4}{p}\right)\cdot \left(\frac{a}{p}\right)=\left(\frac{a}{p}\right)=\left(\frac{-q}{p}\right)
    </md>
    Now 
    <md>
        \left(\frac{-q}{p}\right)=\left(\frac{-1}{p}\right)\left(\frac{q}{p}\right)=(-1)^{\frac{p-1}{2}}\left(\frac{p}{q}\right)(-1)^{\frac{p-1}{2}\frac{q-1}{2}}
    </md>
     Next
     <md>
        \left(\frac{p}{q}\right)=\left(\frac{a+4q}{q}\right)=\left(\frac{a}{q}\right).
     </md>

     So, it remains to show that the exponent on <m>-1</m>:

     <md>
        \frac{p-1}{2}+\frac{p-1}{2}\frac{q-1}{2}
     </md>
     is always even.

     Notice that <m>p</m> and <m>q</m> are congruent to each other modulo <m>4</m>. If <m>p \equiv 1 \pmod{4}</m> then <m>\frac{p-1}{2}</m> is even so the exponent is even.

     If <m>p \equiv q \equiv 3 \pmod{4}</m> then both additive terms in the exponent are odd so the sum is even.

     
     
</p>
</subsection>


</section>